While an experimental vaccine appears to be able to reduce Ebola mortality, so far there are no medicines that have been proven to be suitable for the treatment of existing infections.
An antibody cocktail, ZMapp, initially appeared promising, formal studies showed, however, that it, in terms of preventing deaths, brought fewer benefits than hoped.
In the PALM study, ZMapp was used as a control, i.e. the scientists used it as a starting point and compared the three other treatments with it.
USA Gymnastics supports the letter of the U.S. Olympic Committee and accepts it as an absolute necessity that the Olympic family sets itself for a safe environment for all our athletes.
We agree with the statement of the USOC that the interests of our athletes and clubs and their sports are better served if we drive meaningful changes within our organization instead of a decertification.
USA Gymnastics supports an independent investigation that could shed light on how abuse on the scale described so bravely by the survivors of Larry Nassar could go undetected for so long, and welcomes all necessary and appropriate changes.
USA Gymnastics and the USOC have the same goal - to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible for athletes, so that they can follow their dreams in a safe, positive and self-determined environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski worked as an advisor for John F. Kennedy, as well as for the government around Lyndon B. Johnson.
During the elections in 1976, he advised Carter in foreign policy and then served from 1977 to 1981 in succession to Henry Kissinger as national security adviser (NSA).
As a national security adviser, he supported Carter in the diplomatic handling of world affairs such as the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between the United States and China at the end of the 1970s, the Iranian Revolution, which led to the hostage crisis in Iran in 1979, and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
