This confirms not only that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory that is already widely accepted, but also provides details that fossils in general do not provide, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this bird on the upper side was chestnut-brown and on the lower side light- or carotinoid-colored.
The find also provides insights into the evolution of feathers in birds.
Because dinosaur feathers do not have a well-developed shaft, which is called the rachis, but other features of feathers – hooks and barbules – led the researchers to conclude that the rachis was probably a later evolutionary development than these other features.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flying, but rather for temperature regulation or display. The researchers suspected that the sample, although it was the tail of a young dinosaur, showed the plumage of an adult and not the down of a hatchling.
The researchers claimed that, although this is the tail of a young dinosaur, the sample does not show the feathers of an adult and not the down of a hatchling.
